{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> τέρψις</b>, εως, ἡ, <br /> also ιος [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.AD: Orphica “Fragmenta” 11 \">Refs 5th c.AD+</a>]: (τέρπω):— <b>enjoyment, delight</b>, τινος <b>from</b> or <b>in</b> a thing, τέρψις ἀοιδῆς [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Theogonia” 917, compare 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Ranae” 676 (Lyric poetry); δείπνων τέρψιες 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 9.19, compare 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 2.38 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; χλιδανῆς ἥβης τ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Persae” 544 (_anapaest meter_); κυλίκων 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Ajax” 1201 (Lyric poetry); εἰς τέρψιν τινῶν ἐλθεῖν 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Phoenissae” 195, compare “IT” 797; βραχεῖα τ. ἡδονῆς κακῆς [prev. author] “fragment” 362.23: τ. ἐστί μοι\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>], with <i>infinitive</i>, it is my <b>pleasure</b> to.., ἦν μοι τ. ἐκπεσεῖν χθονός [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 766, compare 775 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: <i>absolutely</i>, <b>joy, delight</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 6th c.BC: Theognis Elegiacus 787, 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “O.” 12.11, 5th c.BC: Bacchylides Lyricus 1.59, 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 611, etc.: _plural_, αἱ διὰ τῶν αἰσθήσεων τ. 1st c.BC: Philodemus Gadarensis Epigrammaticus “D.” 3.14: distinguished from the more general term ἡδονή by 5th c.BC: Prodicus Philosophus cited in 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Topica” 112b23, compare 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Philebus” 11b. \">Refs 6th c.BC+</a>]","strongNumber":"G9426","accentedUnicode":"τέρψις","shortDef":"delight","mediumDef":"delight","stepGloss":"delight","stepTransliteration":"terpsis","_step_Type":"word"}]}